electrodynamics. Indeed, Maxwell's equations predict a *specific*,
computable velocity of electromagnetic radiation. The question becomes:
in what reference frame do Maxwell's equations hold? They *cannot* be
valid in *all* reference frames (which can be in relative motion) as
required by the relativity principle, at least if Newtonian velocity
addition is to hold, since two Newtonian observers in reference frames
in relative motion will measure different velocities of light -- yet
Maxwell's equations predict a *specific* velocity.

Thus Newtonian mechanics and the relativity principle were mutually
contradictory -- until Einstein's beautifully simply reformulation of
kinematics *restored* the principle of relativity that Maxwell's
equations had banished from Newtonian mechanics. The problem lay
squarely in Newtonian kinematics, and Einstein was the first to grasp
this simple point.

