I don't have Akrigg's book handy, but I know that the source
for the story about Southampton having sexual relations
with a man in a tent in Ireland is a letter by William Reynolds,
a former soldier who became mentally ill (probably schizophrenic,
in modern parlance) and wrote many letters in the 1590s to
Lord Burghley and other government officials, letters which survive
because they were put into what amounts to a &quot;nutcase file&quot;.
Reynolds is the one who wrote to Burghley in 1593, a few
months after Shakespeare's *Venus and Adonis* was published,
because he was convinced that the poem had been published
to make Queen Elizabeth fall in love with him. (See Katherine
Duncan-Jones, &quot;Much Ado with Red and White: The Earliest
Readers of Shakespeare's *Venus and Adonis* (1593)&quot;, Review
of English Studies 44 (1993), 479-501.) In a letter from about
1598, Reynolds wrote that while in Ireland, Southampton slept in
a tent with Piers Edmondes, a fellow officer, and that &quot;the
earle Sowthampton would cole [embrace] and huge [hug]
him in his armes and play wantonly wth him.&quot; Reynolds is
not exactly a reliable source, though it's not impossible that
he was reporting an actual rumor.

