Hsu was by no means the first to discard the second postulate.
Indeed, as I have already told you before (but you can neither read nor
remember, so I'm not sure why I bother), that step was taken in as early
as 1909, a scant four years after Einstein's landmark paper, by a
Russian physicist, Ignatowski, who summarized his observation thus (in
Coleman's translation):

&quot;On the basis of the relativity principle alone, it is possible
to prove that a universal cosmic constant must exist, in contrast
to [the method of Einstein], who in parallel with the relativity
principle assumes a priori the velocity of light as a universal
constant.&quot;

Indeed, the fact the second postulate is not a logical necessity is one
of the reasons that I have emphasized, over and over, that Einstein's
great innovation was *not* the second postulate, as many popularizations
suggest, but rather his new kinematics. Einstein was apparently led to
his new kinematics in part by an exploration of the consequences of the
relativity principle coupled with the invariance of the speed of light,
but the important insight in retrospect was Einstein's striking revision
of Newtonian kinematics. Nowadays some people develop and extend the
theory by beginning with Einstein's kinematics together with some
relatively mild assumptions (spatial and temporal uniformity, etc.) and
dispensing with the second postulate, or indeed dispensing with
Einstein's underlying assumption that relativity necessarily involves
electromagnetic theory. Indeed, David Mermin's paper &quot;Relativity
without light&quot; (which I believe appeared while I was still a student --
at any rate, I was certainly aware of it as a student) has been out for
some twenty years; it describes how one can deduce a universal velocity
directly from the relativity principle. Experiment shows that velocity
to be the velocity of light. See also a paper from last year by Pal in
the European Journal of Physics. None of these physicists disputes
either the correctness of or Einstein's priority in the discovery of
relativity.

Many people have since pointed out that, by making alternative
assumptions, one can eliminate the second postulate. But you would
already *know* this if you had actually *read* the Coleman paper you
attempted to cite; indeed, Coleman mentions Ignatowski's observation
*explicitly*. Of course, I realize with sadness that an attempt by you
to read Coleman would be about as effectual as an attempt by my poodle
to do so.

